What is Inheritance?
--------------------------
Inheritance is a mechanism in Java by which one class acquires the properties (variables) and behaviors (methods) of another class.

1. Promotes code reusability
2. Supports method overriding
3. Helps achieve runtime polymorphism

Basic Terminology
----------------------

	Term				Meaning
	------               -------------
Superclass			Parent / Base class
Subclass				Child / Derived class
extends				Keyword used to inherit a class
implements			Used to inherit interfaces

Syntax of Inheritance:
---------------------------
class Parent {
    int a = 10;
}

class Child extends Parent {
    void display() {
        System.out.println(a);
    }
}

Why Inheritance is Needed?
----------------------------------

1. Avoids duplicate code
2. Improves maintainability
3. Establishes IS-A relationship
4. Enables method overriding

Types of Inheritance in Java
----------------------------------
1Ô∏è Single Inheritance
------------------------
One child inherits from one parent.

class A {
    void show() {
        System.out.println("Class A");
    }
}

class B extends A {
}
‚úî Supported in Java

2Ô∏è Multilevel Inheritance
-----------------------------
A class inherits from another derived class.

class A {
    void methodA() {
        System.out.println("A");
    }
}

class B extends A {
    void methodB() {
        System.out.println("B");
    }
}

class C extends B {
    void methodC() {
        System.out.println("C");
    }
}
‚úî Supported in Java

3Ô∏è Hierarchical Inheritance
-------------------------------
Multiple child classes inherit from one parent.

class A {
    void show() {
        System.out.println("Parent");
    }
}

class B extends A {
}

class C extends A {
}
‚úî Supported in Java

4Ô∏è Multiple Inheritance (‚ùå NOT supported with classes)
-------------------------------------------------------------------
A class cannot inherit from more than one class.

‚ùå Invalid in Java
class C extends A, B {
}

‚ùå Causes Diamond Problem

5Ô∏è Hybrid Inheritance (‚ùå with classes)
----------------------------------------------
Combination of two or more types.

‚ùå Not supported using classes
‚úî Achieved using interfaces

üîπ Why Java Does NOT Support Multiple Inheritance (Classes)?
Diamond Problem
----------------------
      A
     /   \
   B   C
     \   /
      D  ‚ùì If A has a method ‚Üí which version should D use?

üëâ To avoid ambiguity, Java does not allow multiple inheritance with classes.

Inheritance Using interface (Multiple Inheritance ‚úî)
---------------------------------------------------------------
interface A {
    void show();
}

interface B {
    void display();
}

class C implements A, B {
    public void show() {
        System.out.println("A method");
    }

    public void display() {
        System.out.println("B method");
    }
}

‚úî Multiple inheritance achieved safely

super Keyword in Inheritance
------------------------------------
Uses of super
1. Access parent class variable
2. Call parent class method
3. Call parent class constructor

class A {
    int x = 10;
}

class B extends A {
    int x = 20;

    void display() {
        System.out.println(super.x);
    }
}

Method Overriding
-----------------------
When a child class provides a specific implementation of a parent class method.

class A {
    void show() {
        System.out.println("Parent");
    }
}

class B extends A {
    @Override
    void show() {
        System.out.println("Child");
    }
}

‚úî Happens at runtime
‚úî Used for polymorphism

Rules of Inheritance in Java
----------------------------------

‚úî Child class inherits public & protected members
‚ùå Private members are not inherited
‚úî Constructors are not inherited
‚úî One class can extend only one class
‚úî final class cannot be inherited
‚úî final method cannot be overridden

Advantages of Inheritance
--------------------------------
1. Code reusability
2. Reduced redundancy
3. Faster development
4. Easy maintenance
5. Supports polymorphism

Limitations of Inheritance
-------------------------------
1. Tight coupling
2. Increases complexity
3. Multiple inheritance not supported (classes)